It seems you require a comprehensive overview of grammatical number, presented with a certain... flair. Very well. Let's illuminate this rather foundational, yet frequently convoluted, aspect of [linguistics](/Linguistics), shall we? Do try to keep up.

---

### Use of grammar in a language to express number

One might think counting is straightforward, but in [linguistics](/Linguistics), even that simple act becomes a [grammatical feature](/Feature_(linguistics))—or rather, a labyrinth of features. This delightful complexity, known as grammatical number, manifests across nouns, pronouns, adjectives, and verb [agreement](/Agreement_(linguistics)), meticulously quantifying referents (or attempting to). Most languages, including the rather unremarkable English, settle for a binary distinction: singular or [plural](/Plural). However, for those with a more discerning palate for numerical precision, some languages offer a [dual](/Dual_(grammatical_number)) (precisely two), a trial (exactly three), a paucal (a vague 'few'), or an assortment of other, equally specific, or frustratingly imprecise, arrangements. It seems even basic enumeration requires a certain level of commitment.

And just when you thought you had a handle on 'number,' [linguistics](/Linguistics) throws another curveball. The term also awkwardly moonlights to describe distinctions within [grammatical aspect](/Grammatical_aspect), indicating the *frequency* of an event—think [semelfactive](/Semelfactive) (once) versus iterative (repeatedly). Don't confuse the two; it's a common, if entirely avoidable, rookie mistake. For that particular rabbit hole, you'll want to consult the entry on [Grammatical aspect](/Grammatical_aspect) itself, if you have the stamina.

### Overview

It appears the human compulsion to categorize extends even to quantities. A vast majority of the world's languages, in their infinite wisdom, employ formal mechanisms to delineate numerical distinctions. The most ubiquitous, and frankly, least imaginative, is the straightforward singular-plural dichotomy, exemplified by English's 'car' versus 'cars' or 'child' versus the delightfully irregular 'children.' Such rudimentary systems are merely the tip of the iceberg, of course. For those prepared to delve into the truly intricate and occasionally baffling expressions of quantity, more elaborate systems await below. Don't say I didn't warn you.

At its core, [grammatical number](/Grammatical_category) functions as a [morphological category](/Morphology_(linguistics)), a linguistic mechanism that encodes [quantity](/Quantity) through systematic [inflection](/Inflection) or [agreement](/Agreement_(linguistics)) patterns. To illustrate this concept, consider these profoundly exciting English sentences:

*   That apple on the table is fresh.
*   Those two apples on the table are fresh.

Here, the specific quantity of apples isn't just a fleeting thought; it's meticulously encoded. The noun itself undergoes a transformation: 'apple' denotes a solitary item (singular), while 'apples' signals a multiplicity (plural). But why stop there? The [demonstrative](/Demonstrative) pronoun, 'that' versus 'those,' also dutifully aligns with the count. And, naturally, the verb, 'is' versus 'are,' must also fall into line, demonstrating a pervasive [agreement](/Agreement_(linguistics)) across the sentence. One might observe, with a sigh, that in the second example, all this elaborate signaling becomes entirely [redundant](/Redundancy_(linguistics)), given the explicit presence of the numeral *two*. But consistency, it seems, is its own reward, even when it serves no practical purpose.

So, when does a language truly *have* [grammatical number](/Grammatical_category), rather than merely hinting at it? It's when its [noun](/Noun) forms are not merely distinct, but are rigorously sorted into [morphological classes](/Morphology_(linguistics)) based on quantity, adhering to two fundamental criteria:

*   Every [noun](/Noun) form must unequivocally belong to a specific number class, effectively partitioning them into mutually exclusive categories by number. No fence-sitting allowed.
*   Furthermore, any [modifiers](/Modifier_(linguistics)) associated with these nouns (such as adjectives) and the [verbs](/Verb) they interact with must also possess distinct forms for each numerical subclass. These elements are then expected to [inflect](/Inflection) with unwavering precision, matching the number of the nouns they modify or agree with. This, my dear reader, is what we call an [agreement category](/Agreement_(linguistics)).

English, in its usual half-hearted manner, only partially commits to this ideal. While most [nouns](/Noun) and [pronouns](/Pronoun) are indeed assigned a singular or plural status (with notable, context-dependent exceptions like '[fish](/Fish)', '[cannon](/Cannon)', or the notoriously ambiguous '[you](/You)'), the system is far from rigorous. Certain noun [modifiers](/Modifier_(linguistics))—specifically the [demonstrative](/Demonstrative) determiners like 'this' and 'these'—and finite [verbs](/Verb) do perform this dutiful [agreement](/Agreement_(linguistics)). One correctly says 'this car' and 'these cars'; to utter '*this cars' or '*these car' would be a grammatical transgression, a minor sacrilege. Yet, English [adjectives](/Adjective) remain stubbornly impervious to number [inflection](/Inflection), and a significant portion of verb forms refuse to differentiate between singular and plural, as evidenced by the identical 'She/They went,' 'She/They can go,' 'She/They had gone,' and 'She/They will go.' It's a system that values convenience over comprehensive logical consistency, much like most human endeavors.

A rather common, and often overlooked, distinction in languages is that between [count nouns](/Count_noun) and [mass nouns](/Mass_noun). It's quite simple, really: only [count nouns](/Count_noun) are granted the freedom to flit between singular and plural forms with unrestrained abandon. [Mass nouns](/Mass_noun), on the other hand—those nebulous concepts like 'milk,' 'gold,' or 'furniture'—typically remain stubbornly invariant, refusing to submit to the indignity of pluralization. [2] (Though, naturally, there are always exceptions designed to complicate matters. A [mass noun](/Mass_noun) 'X' might, on rare occasions, be pressed into service as a [count noun](/Count_noun) when one wishes to categorize distinct *types* of 'X' into an enumerable collection. Imagine, if you must, a cheesemaker, in a moment of whimsical linguistic rebellion, referring to 'goat, sheep, and cow milk' collectively as 'milks.' Such linguistic acrobatics are usually reserved for specific, technical contexts, or when one is simply trying to be difficult.)

It's almost a relief to note that not *every* language has burdened itself with [grammatical number](/Grammatical_category). In these more pragmatic systems, quantity is conveyed with refreshing directness: either through explicit [numerals](/Numeral_(linguistics)) (like 'three' or 'seven') or, less directly, via optional [quantifiers](/Quantifier_(linguistics)) (such as 'many' or 'some'). Curiously, many of these languages, perhaps feeling a void, often 'compensate' for this absence of grammatical number by developing an extensive, and often bewildering, array of [measure words](/Measure_word). These classifiers are then obligatorily used with nouns, adding another layer of categorization where simple pluralization might have sufficed. One must wonder if it's truly compensation, or merely an alternative form of complexity.

[Joseph Greenberg](/Joseph_Greenberg), in his rather ambitious quest to identify [linguistic universals](/Greenberg%27s_linguistic_universals), posited a hierarchy for number categories. His pronouncement, delivered with the certainty of a cosmic decree, stated: "No language has a trial number unless it has a dual. No language has a dual unless it has a plural." [3] A neat, tidy package, wouldn't you agree? Unfortunately, like many grand theories, it conveniently overlooks the [paucal](/Paucal_number), which, much like an uninvited guest, often shows up without adhering to established protocols. [4] It seems even universals have their exceptions, or perhaps, their blind spots.

### Geographical distribution

The geographical spread of obligatory plural marking offers a rather uneven tapestry, much like human history itself. This particular linguistic requirement, where every [noun](/Noun) must declare its numerical allegiance, is a staple across the languages of [western and northern Eurasia](/Eurasiatic_languages) and extends through [most parts of Africa](/Languages_of_Africa). Beyond these regions, however, the linguistic landscape becomes far more variegated—a testament to human inconsistency. Optional plural marking, a more relaxed approach to quantity, is prevalent in [Southeast and East Asia](/East_Asian_languages) and among [Australian languages](/Australian_languages). The truly minimalist, those languages that completely eschew plural marking, find their stronghold particularly in [New Guinea](/Papuan_languages) and, again, in [Australian languages](/Australian_languages).

Beyond these [areal correlations](/Areal_feature), a deeper pattern emerges, linking this phenomenon to [morphological typology](/Morphological_typology). [Isolating languages](/Isolating_languages), those that prefer words to remain uninflected and distinct, tend to favor either no plural marking at all or, at best, optional marking. This trend is quite pronounced in Africa, where the absence or optionality of plural marking is a hallmark of the [isolating languages](/Isolating_languages) of West Africa. [5] [6] It seems that some languages, much like some people, simply prefer not to be tied down by unnecessary grammatical obligations.

### Types of number

#### Singular and plural

(Main article: [Plural](/Plural))

The most fundamental, and frankly, least imaginative, numerical distinction a language can conjure is the simple binary of singular and plural. The singular, with its unwavering commitment to solitude, refers to precisely one referent. The plural, a more accommodating category, embraces anything beyond that singular unit—two, three, a million, or even fractions thereof, depending on the language's particular quirks. English, in its characteristic simplicity, provides a straightforward illustration: [7]

*   dog (singular, a solitary canine)
*   dogs (plural, indicating two or more, a veritable pack)

English, ever the minimalist, marks this distinction on nouns and, with peculiar selectivity, on verbs, specifically in the third person. Observe: "my dog watch*es* television" (singular) versus "my dog*s* watch television" (plural). [7] However, one would be foolish to assume such a pattern is universal. [Wambaya](/Wambaya_language), for instance, opts to mark number exclusively on nouns, leaving its verbs unburdened by such distinctions. [8] Conversely, [Onondaga](/Onondaga_language) finds it perfectly logical to mark number on verbs but not on nouns. [9]

For a more robust commitment to numerical agreement, one might look to [Latin](/Latin), which, in its ancient wisdom, insisted on different singular and plural forms for nouns, verbs, *and* adjectives—a stark contrast to English's rather lax approach where adjectives remain stubbornly invariant regardless of number. [10] And then there’s [Tundra Nenets](/Tundra_Nenets_language), a language that, with admirable (or perhaps excessive) zeal, extends singular and plural marking to nouns, verbs, adjectives, adverbs, and even [postpositions](/Preposition_and_postposition). [11] It seems some languages truly commit to their grammatical choices.

Despite these varied manifestations, the most consistently observed part of speech to exhibit a number distinction across languages is [pronouns](/Pronoun). [12] [13] They are, after all, the linguistic stand-ins for individuals and groups, and thus are often compelled to reflect their quantity. The [Wayoró language](/Wayor%C3%B3_language) offers a clear example of a personal pronoun system that elegantly distinguishes between singular and plural forms, a simple yet effective binary for referring to individuals and groups, excluding or including the speaker as needed: [14]

| | Singular | Plural |
|---|---|---|
| First (exc.) | on | ote |
| First (inc.) | —N/a | txire |
| Second | en | djat |
| Third | ndeke | ndeat |

One might note the logical absence of a singular form for the first person inclusive, as 'we' inherently implies more than one. A minor point, perhaps, but one that highlights the inherent logic, or lack thereof, in linguistic systems.

#### Dual

(Main article: [Dual (grammatical number)](/Dual_(grammatical_number)))

While the singular embraces solitude and the plural a vague multiplicity, the [dual number](/Dual_(grammatical_number)) insists on precision, denoting *exactly* two items. It's for when 'one' isn't enough, but 'many' is too imprecise. The [Camsá language](/Cams%C3%A1_language) illustrates this beautifully, or at least, functionally: [15]

*   *kes̈* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"dog" (a singular, lonely dog)
*   *kes̈ at* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"two dogs" (a pair, distinctly dual)
*   *kes̈ ëng* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"dogs" (a plural, three or more, once the dual has done its job)

The presence of a [dual](/Dual_(grammatical_number)) category, however, complicates the very meaning of 'plural.' In languages that boast a full singular/dual/plural paradigm, the exact numerical boundary of 'plural' becomes contingent on whether the [dual](/Dual_(grammatical_number)) is obligatory or merely facultative (optional). [16] In systems where the [dual](/Dual_(grammatical_number)) is an absolute requirement, 'plural' sheds its English-centric meaning of 'two or more' and narrows its scope to strictly 'three or more.' This rigorous distinction is observed in languages like [Sanskrit](/Sanskrit) [17], [North Mansi](/Mansi_language) [18], and [Alutiiq](/Alutiiq_language) [19].

Conversely, in languages where the [dual](/Dual_(grammatical_number)) is facultative, one retains the option to refer to two items using either the [dual](/Dual_(grammatical_number)) *or* the [plural](/Plural) form, rendering 'plural' once again as 'two or more.' This more flexible approach is characteristic of modern Arabic dialects [20], certain [Inuktitut](/Inuktitut) dialects [21], and [Yandruwandha](/Yandruwandha_language) [22]. Some languages, perhaps indecisive, even blend these approaches: in [Slovene](/Slovene_language), the [dual](/Dual_(grammatical_number)) is obligatory for [pronouns](/Pronoun) but remains facultative for [nouns](/Noun) [23]. [Comanche](/Comanche_language) shows a similar gradient, making the [dual](/Dual_(grammatical_number)) obligatory when referring to humans, facultative for other animate nouns, and a rarity for inanimate nouns [24]. It seems even grammatical categories have their priorities.

The application of the [dual number](/Dual_(grammatical_number)) can also be surprisingly restricted. In the possessive noun forms of [Northern Sámi](/Northern_S%C3%A1mi), for instance, the *possessor* may be in the [dual number](/Dual_(grammatical_number)), but the noun *possessed* itself is limited to either singular or plural [25]. In some [Polynesian languages](/Polynesian_languages), including [Samoan](/Samoan_language) [26], [Tuvaluan](/Tuvaluan_language) [27] (with a minor, almost charming, exception for a specific verb [a]), and [Māori](/M%C4%81ori_language) [29], [pronouns](/Pronoun) are the *only* part of speech that bother with a [dual](/Dual_(grammatical_number)) form.

[Maltese](/Maltese_language) takes this selectivity to an almost absurd degree: the [dual](/Dual_(grammatical_number)) exists for merely 30 specific nouns, and of those, only eight (such as 'hour,' 'day,' 'week,' 'month,' 'year,' 'once,' 'hundred,' and 'thousand') demand obligatory [dual](/Dual_(grammatical_number)) marking. Other nouns, like 'egg' or 'branch,' may take a facultative [dual](/Dual_(grammatical_number)) [30]. And then there's [Mezquital Otomi](/Northwestern_Otomi), where the [dual](/Dual_(grammatical_number)) is reserved exclusively for conversations between adult males [31]. The intricacies are truly endless, aren't they?

The [Māori language](/M%C4%81ori_language) offers another clear illustration of a pronominal system that distinguishes the [dual](/Dual_(grammatical_number)) from singular and plural: [32]

| | Singular | Dual | Plural |
|---|---|---|---|
| First (exc.) | au/ahau | māua | mātou |
| First (inc.) | —N/a | tāua | tātou |
| Second | koe | kōrua | koutou |
| Third | ia | rāua | rātou |

Historically, the [dual number](/Dual_(grammatical_number)) was a regular, if demanding, feature across all nouns and adjectives in [Proto-Indo-European language](/Proto-Indo-European_language), a linguistic ancestor from roughly 4000 BCE. It was inherited, in various attenuated forms, by many of its [prehistoric](/Prehistory), [protohistoric](/Protohistory), [ancient](/Ancient_history), and [medieval](/Middle_Ages) descendants. Yet, its persistence in modern [Indo-European languages](/Indo-European_languages) is a rarity, a linguistic fossil more than a living system. It managed to survive in [Proto-Germanic language](/Proto-Germanic_language) within the first and second person [pronouns](/Pronoun), from which it was subsequently inherited by [Old English](/Old_English), [Old High German](/Old_High_German), [Old Low German](/Old_Saxon), [Early Old Swedish](/Old_Swedish), [Old Norwegian](/Old_Norwegian), [Old Icelandic](/Old_Norse), and [Gothic](/Gothic_language). [33] [34] Icelandic maintained this dual until the 18th century, and some dialects of [Faroese language](/Faroese_language) clung to it until at least the late 19th century, with certain [North Frisian language](/North_Frisian_language) dialects preserving it through the 20th century. [33] [34]

From [Proto-Greek language](/Proto-Greek_language), the [dual](/Dual_(grammatical_number)) migrated into [Ancient Greek](/Ancient_Greek) [35] [36], and from [Proto-Indo-Iranian language](/Proto-Indo-Iranian_language), it found a home in [Sanskrit](/Sanskrit) [37] [17]. Even [Proto-Slavic language](/Proto-Slavic_language) carried the torch, leading to its continued existence in [Slovene language](/Slovene_language) and the [Sorbian languages](/Sorbian_languages) today [38]. [Indo-European languages](/Indo-European_languages) that long ago discarded the [dual](/Dual_(grammatical_number)) still sometimes bear faint, residual traces of its former glory. Consider the English distinctions: *both* versus *all*, *either* versus *any*, and *neither* versus *none*. These pairings subtly hint at a lost precision. Curiously, the Norwegian *både*, a cognate of English *both*, has broadened its scope to encompass more than two items, as in *både epler, pærer, og druer* (literally "both apples, pears, and grapes"). Linguistic evolution, it seems, has a sense of irony. [39]

#### Trial

The [trial number](/Trial_number) is for when two isn't enough, but 'a few' is too vague. It denotes *exactly* three items, a commitment to a specific, small grouping. The [Awa language (Papua New Guinea)](/Awa_language_(Papua_New_Guinea)) provides a crisp example: [40]

*   *iya* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"dog" (singular)
*   *iya tade* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"two dogs" (dual)
*   *iya tado* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"three dogs" (trial, precisely)
*   *iya madi* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"dogs" (plural, anything beyond three)

It is remarkably uncommon for a language to mark the [trial](/Trial_number) on nouns [41], with some sources even boldly claiming its non-existence in this capacity [42] [43]. Yet, a few defiant languages do. Besides [Awa](/Awa_language_(Papua_New_Guinea)), [Arabana language](/Arabana_language) [44] [45], [Urama](/Kiwai_language) [46], and [Angaataha language](/Angaataha_language) [47] possess this rare [noun](/Noun)-marking trial. Far more frequently, languages opt for [trial pronouns](/Trial_number), [42] [43] a phenomenon observed in Austronesian languages such as [Larike](/Wakasihu_language) [48] [49], [Tolai](/Tolai_language) [50], [Raga](/Raga_language) [51], and [Wamesa](/Wamesa_language) [52]. A particularly minimalist example is [Nukna language](/Nukna_language), which offers only a single [trial pronoun](/Trial_number), *nanggula*, serving for both second and third persons [53]. The trial may also, less commonly, be marked on verbs, as demonstrated in [Lenakel language](/Lenakel_language) [54].

The [Larike language](/Wakasihu_language) showcases a full set of trial pronouns:

| | Singular | Dual | Trial | Plural |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| First (exc.) | aʔu | arua | aridu | ami |
| First (inc.) | —N/a | itua | itidu | ite |
| Second | ane | irua | iridu | imi |
| Third | mane | matua | matidu | mati |

While the [dual](/Dual_(grammatical_number)) can be either obligatory or facultative, [Greville Corbett](/Greville_G_Corbett), a linguist who has spent an inordinate amount of time categorizing such things, notes that no known cases of an obligatory [trial](/Trial_number) exist [55]. This suggests the [trial](/Trial_number) might always be facultative, a choice rather than a mandate. However, a language might simultaneously possess a facultative [dual](/Dual_(grammatical_number)) and a facultative [trial](/Trial_number), like [Larike](/Wakasihu_language), or an obligatory [dual](/Dual_(grammatical_number)) alongside a facultative [trial](/Trial_number), as seen in [Ngan'gi language](/Ngan%27gi_language) [55].

The vast majority of languages featuring a [trial](/Trial_number) belong to the Austronesian family, with most non-Austronesian examples found in the nearby region of Oceania [56]. This latter category notably includes the Austronesian-influenced [English creole languages](/English-based_creole_languages) of [Tok Pisin](/Tok_Pisin) [57], [Bislama](/Bislama) [58], and [Pijin language](/Pijin_language) [59]. In Australia, the [trial](/Trial_number) can also be found across a diverse array of [Australian Aboriginal languages](/Australian_Aboriginal_languages) from various language families [b]. In Indonesia, [trial pronouns](/Trial_number) are a common feature in the storytelling traditions of [Abun language](/Abun_language), a potential [language isolate](/Language_isolate) [69]. On the Solomon Islands, [Touo language](/Touo_language) (either a [Central Solomon language](/Central_Solomon_languages) or another [language isolate](/Language_isolate)) employs [trial pronouns](/Trial_number) with remarkable frequency. Consequently, bilingual speakers of Touo and Pijin tend to use [trial pronouns](/Trial_number) far more often in Pijin than other speakers, for whom the [trial](/Trial_number) is generally less common than the [dual](/Dual_(grammatical_number)) [70]. A truly rare example of a spoken language outside Oceania that features the [trial](/Trial_number) (on both [pronouns](/Pronoun) and [verbs](/Verb)) is [Muklom Tangsa](/Tangsa_language), spoken in northeast India [71].

#### Paucal

The [paucal number](/Paucal_number) is the linguistic equivalent of a shrug: it represents 'a few,' a small, inexactly numbered group of items. It's for when you can't be bothered to count precisely, but know it's more than one or two. In [Motuna language](/Siwai_language), this looks like: [72]

*   *mahkata* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"dog" (singular)
*   *mahkata karo* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"two dogs" (dual)
*   *mahkata naa* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"a few dogs" (paucal, an indeterminate small group)
*   *mahkata ngung* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"dogs" (plural, anything larger)

Almost all languages that indulge in a [paucal](/Paucal_number) also possess a [dual](/Dual_(grammatical_number)) [73] [74]. Interestingly, [nouns](/Noun) in [Mocoví language](/Mocov%C3%AD_language) simplify matters, distinguishing only singular, paucal, and plural [73] [75]. The [pronouns](/Pronoun) in [Mussau-Emira language](/Mussau-Emira_language) [76] [77] and [Lihir language](/Lihir_language) [78] showcase a more elaborate system, including dual, trial, and paucal forms.

The [Lihir language](/Lihir_language) provides a detailed example of such a pronominal system:

| | Singular | Dual | Trial | Paucal | Plural |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| First (exc.) | yo | gel | getol | gehet | ge |
| First (inc.) | —N/a | kito | kitol | kitahet | giet |
| Second | wa | gol | gotol | gohet | go |
| Third | e | dul | dietol | diehet | die |

The lower bound of the [paucal](/Paucal_number) is, predictably, context-dependent, usually defined by the other number categories available. In singular/paucal/plural systems, the [paucal](/Paucal_number) begins at two. However, with the addition of a [dual](/Dual_(grammatical_number)), the [paucal](/Paucal_number) politely waits until three. The upper bound, however, remains frustratingly inexact, a fluid concept that shifts with both language and communicative context [79]. It has been documented to extend up to approximately 5 in [Warndarrang language](/Warndarrang_language) [80], around 6 in [Baiso language](/Baiso_language) [62], 10 in Arabic [81] [82], and even up to 10 or 15 in [Murrinh-patha language](/Murrinh-patha_language) [78]. In [Manam language](/Manam_language), the primary determinant for using the [paucal](/Paucal_number) isn't a strict numerical range, but rather whether the referents form a single, cohesive group; thus, while most common for groups of 3 to 5, it has been observed for groups exceeding 20 [83]. In [Paamese language](/Paamese_language), the [paucal](/Paucal_number) is heavily influenced by relative group size compared to the [plural](/Plural). A group of 2,000 people, for instance, might be described using the [paucal](/Paucal_number) if contrasted with a group of 100,000 referred to in the [plural](/Plural), even though the [paucal](/Paucal_number) generally denotes 12 or fewer [84]. It seems quantity is often in the eye of the beholder, or at least, the speaker.

Much like the [dual](/Dual_(grammatical_number)), the specific words and parts of speech that may be marked with the [paucal](/Paucal_number) vary considerably across languages. [Baiso](/Baiso_language) restricts the [paucal](/Paucal_number) to nouns, excluding [pronouns](/Pronoun) [62], while [Yimas language](/Yimas_language) does the exact opposite, reserving it solely for [pronouns](/Pronoun) [85]. In [Meryam Mir](/Meriam_language), the [paucal](/Paucal_number) primarily adorns verbs [86] [87]. [Avar language](/Avar_language) is particularly selective, applying the [paucal](/Paucal_number) to only about 90 specific nouns, including 'brush,' 'spade,' 'snake,' and 'daughter-in-law' (the sole kin term in Avar to accept the [paucal](/Paucal_number)) [88]. [Takivatan Bunun](/Bunun_language) features a [paucal](/Paucal_number) exclusively in its distal [demonstratives](/Demonstrative) when referring to people [89].

It is a common, if slightly inconvenient, linguistic phenomenon for former [trials](/Trial_number) to undergo semantic evolution and become [paucals](/Paucal_number). Indeed, many Austronesian languages retain [paucal markers](/Paucal_number) that are etymologically traceable to the numeral 'three,' a ghostly echo of their original usage [90] [91]. The transformation of [duals](/Dual_(grammatical_number)) into [paucals](/Paucal_number) is less frequent [92], though it has been observed in some Arabic dialects [93] [94]. These etymologically-derived paucals are, rather predictably, sometimes mislabeled as [trials](/Trial_number) [c]. For instance, [trial pronouns](/Trial_number) were once broadly attributed to all Kiwaian languages [98] [99], but it is now recognized that many of these actually possess a [paucal](/Paucal_number) instead [d]. Linguist Michael Cysouw, with a touch of exasperation, has even suggested that most languages reported to have [trials](/Trial_number) are, in fact, merely miscategorized [paucals](/Paucal_number), and that true [trials](/Trial_number) are exceedingly rare [91]. However, some grammarians remain steadfast. [Luise Hercus](/Luise_Hercus), for example, explicitly stated in her grammar of [Arabana](/Arabana_language) that its [noun](/Noun)-marked [trial](/Trial_number) is a true [trial](/Trial_number) and cannot function as a [paucal](/Paucal_number) [104]. Similar assertions have been made for [trial pronouns](/Trial_number) in [Larike](/Wakasihu_language) [105] and [Anejom̃ language](/Aneityum_language) [106]. The debate, it seems, continues to rage.

[Russian language](/Russian_language) offers a particularly intriguing, if somewhat perplexing, construction often referred to as [paucal numerals](/Paucal_number) [107], the count form [108] [e], the adnumerative [110], or the genitive of quantification [111]. When a [noun](/Noun) in the [nominative case](/Nominative_case) is quantified by the numerals 2, 3, or 4, the noun itself shifts to the [genitive singular](/Genitive_case). However, when quantified by 5 or above, it assumes the [genitive plural](/Genitive_case) [f]. Many linguists, understandably, have described these as [paucal constructions](/Paucal_number) [114]. Yet, some dissent, arguing that a Russian [noun](/Noun) cannot, by itself, be declined to convey a meaning of "anywhere between 2 and 4" [115]. Similar constructions, designed to complicate matters further, are found in other [Slavic languages](/Slavic_languages), including [Polish language](/Polish_language) [116], [Serbo-Croatian](/Serbo-Croatian) [117], and [Slovene language](/Slovene_language). [Slovene](/Slovene_language), with its existing regular [dual](/Dual_(grammatical_number)), creates a four-way distinction: singular for 1, dual for 2, plural for 3 or 4, and [genitive plural](/Genitive_case) for 5 or more [118]. It's enough to make one question the purpose of language.

#### Greater paucal

The [greater paucal](/Paucal_number) number is, as its name suggests, a larger [paucal](/Paucal_number) category, referring to an inexactly numbered group that is *larger* than a regular, smaller [paucal](/Paucal_number). Because, naturally, one [paucal](/Paucal_number) isn't enough. It can be found in the [pronouns](/Pronoun) of the Austronesian language of [Sursurunga language](/Sursurunga_language), which boasts a five-way distinction: singular, dual, paucal, greater paucal, and plural. The [Sursurunga paucal](/Paucal_number) is typically employed for smaller groups, usually around three or four, or for entire nuclear families, regardless of size. The [Sursurunga greater paucal](/Paucal_number), however, is reserved for groups of four or more (and *must* be used instead of the [plural](/Plural) for a group comprising two or more dyads). This, predictably, leads to some overlap; a family of four could, with equal grammatical validity, be referred to by either of the paucals [119]. This intricate distinction manifests in [Sursurunga's personal pronouns](/Pronoun) and across two distinct sets of possessive [pronouns](/Pronoun)—one for edible items, and another for non-edible things [120].

The [Sursurunga pronouns](/Sursurunga_language) illustrate this impressive, if somewhat exhausting, system: [121] [119]

| | Singular | Dual | Paucal | Greater paucal | Plural |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| First (exc.) | iau | giur | gimtul | gimhat | gim |
| First (inc.) | —N/a | gitar | gitul | githat | git |
| Second | u | gaur | gamtul | gamhat | gam |
| Third | a | diar | ditul | dihat | di |

#### Quadral

The [quadral number](/Quadral_number) denotes precisely four items. Its apparent existence is almost entirely confined to [pronouns](/Pronoun), and specifically those found in the languages of Oceania or, rather surprisingly, in [sign languages](/Sign_language). Whether the [quadral](/Quadral_number) genuinely exists in natural language remains a point of contention; some linguists have dismissed it as an extant category [122], while others, perhaps more open-minded, have accepted it [123]. Languages previously described as having a [quadral](/Quadral_number), such as [Sursurunga](/Sursurunga_language), have since been reanalyzed as possessing a [paucal](/Paucal_number) instead [124] [119].

Much like [trial forms](/Trial_number), [quadral forms](/Quadral_number) of [pronouns](/Pronoun) have been reported in the Melanesian pidgins of [Tok Pisin](/Tok_Pisin) [57] [125], [Bislama](/Bislama) [126], and [Pijin language](/Pijin_language) [127]. However, while grammatically possible, their actual usage is rare, with [plural forms](/Plural) almost universally employed in their stead. It seems even in these languages, precision has its limits.

Many different [sign languages](/Sign_language), however, have been explicitly described as featuring [quadral pronoun forms](/Quadral_number) [g] [h]. [Estonian Sign Language](/Estonian_Sign_Language) has even been credited with a [quadral](/Quadral_number) for nouns [145].

[Marshallese language](/Marshallese_language) has been presented as a language where the [quadral](/Quadral_number) is a regular feature of its pronoun system [146] [147]. However, the apparent [Marshallese quadral](/Quadral_number) can, besides meaning exactly four, also be used rhetorically in speeches to larger groups, imbuing a sense of individual intimacy. According to [Greville Corbett](/Greville_G_Corbett), this alternate use means it is more accurately classified as a [paucal](/Paucal_number) [148]. Yet, there is no universal consensus on this interpretation; the definitive 2016 reference grammar of [Marshallese](/Marshallese_language) by [Byron W. Bender](/Byron_W._Bender), an expert in the language, steadfastly refers to it as a [quadral](/Quadral_number) [147]. Beyond singular, dual, trial, and quadral (or paucal), [Marshallese](/Marshallese_language) further distinguishes two distinct [plural forms](/Plural): one for five or more, and another for two or more (termed 'multiple' and 'plural absolute,' respectively). This creates a partially overlapping six-way number distinction, a system designed, it would seem, for maximum specificity and potential confusion [147] [149] [150]. [Kove language](/Kove_language) reportedly features a pronoun system similar to [Marshallese](/Marshallese_language), but with an added layer: its [plural](/Plural) (2+) is divided into categories for members of the same family versus members of different families, resulting in an impressive seven-way distinction [151].

The [Marshallese pronouns](/Marshallese_language) (Rālik dialect) are a testament to this complexity:

| | Singular | Dual | Trial | Quadral or Paucal | Multiple (5+) | Plural (2+) |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| First (exc.) | ña | kōmro | kōmjeel | kōm(je)eañ | kōmwōj | kōm |
| First (inc.) | —N/a | kōjro | kōjjeel | kōjeañ | kōjwōj | kōj |
| Second | kwe | koṃro | koṃjeel | koṃ(je)eañ | koṃwōj | koṃ |
| Third | e | erro | erjeel | er(je)jeañ | erwōj | er |

A few other languages have also been claimed to possess [quadral pronouns](/Quadral_number). [Robert Blust](/Robert_Blust) and other scholars have identified them in some of the Austronesian [Kenyah languages](/Kenyah_languages), specifically the highland Lepoʼ Sawa dialect spoken in [Long Anap](/Long_Anap) [152] [153] [154]. However, published information on this specific dialect's pronouns is scarce, and an investigation into the lowland Lebo’ Vo’ dialect revealed a [paucal](/Paucal_number) rather than a [quadral](/Quadral_number) [153]. A [quadral](/Quadral_number) claim has also been put forth for the animate [demonstrative pronouns](/Demonstrative) in [Nauruan language](/Nauruan_language) [155]. Outside the Austronesian family, the storytelling of [Abun language](/Abun_language) reportedly frequently incorporates [quadral pronouns](/Quadral_number) in addition to [trial ones](/Trial_number) [69]. Perhaps the only known spoken language outside Oceania to have a claimed [quadral](/Quadral_number) is [Apinayé language](/Apinay%C3%A9_language) of Brazil, which records a third person pronominal prefix meaning "they four," though this has seen minimal research or description [156] [157].

In some Austronesian languages that employ a singular/dual/trial/plural pronoun system, the [plural forms](/Plural) bear an etymological connection to the number four. This curious fact has prompted suggestions, and even assertions, that a true [quadral](/Quadral_number) once existed historically, only to later morph into a generalized [plural form](/Plural) [i]. Thus, it has been hypothesized that the [quadral](/Quadral_number) was present in [Proto-Oceanic language](/Proto-Oceanic_language) [159] and Proto-Southern Vanuatu [166].

#### Quintal

The [quintal number](/Quintal_number) designates precisely five items. Apparent examples of its use are almost exclusively found in [pronouns](/Pronoun) within [sign languages](/Sign_language). Much like the [quadral](/Quadral_number), its very existence is debated, with only certain classifications accepting it as a legitimate category.

Following the pattern of [trial](/Trial_number) and [quadral forms](/Quadral_number), rare [quintal forms](/Quintal_number) of [pronouns](/Pronoun) have been reported in [Tok Pisin](/Tok_Pisin) [57] and [Bislama](/Bislama) [126]. These languages tend to insert numerals directly to represent exact numbers of referents. For example, in [Bislama](/Bislama), the numerals *tu* (two) and *tri* (three) are integrated into the second person [pronouns](/Pronoun) *yutufala* (dual) and *yutrifala* (trial). While theoretically these forms have no specific numerical limit, in practice, they usually cease at three, perhaps due to sheer exhaustion.

The [Bislama pronouns](/Bislama) demonstrate this numeral incorporation: [167]

| | Standard | Rare | Standard |
|---|---|---|---|
| | Singular | Dual | Trial | Quadral | Quintal | ... | Plural |
| First (exc.) | mi | mitufala | mitrifala | mifofala | mifaefala | ... | mifala |
| First (inc.) | —N/a | yumitufala | yumitrifala | yumifofala | yumifaefala | ... | yumi |
| Second | yu | yutufala | yutrifala | yufofala | yufaefala | ... | yufala |
| Third | em | tufala | trifala | fofala | faefala | ... | olgeta |

[Sign languages](/Sign_language) described as possessing a [quintal](/Quintal_number) in addition to the [quadral](/Quadral_number) include [American Sign Language](/American_Sign_Language) [128] [129], [Argentine Sign Language](/Argentine_Sign_Language) [130], [British Sign Language](/British_Sign_Language) [132], [German Sign Language](/German_Sign_Language) [134] [135], [Levantine Arabic Sign Language](/Levantine_Arabic_Sign_Language) [139], and [Ugandan Sign Language](/Ugandan_Sign_Language) [142].

The very validity of categorizing [sign language](/Sign_language) [pronouns](/Pronoun) as truly having a [quadral](/Quadral_number) or a [quintal](/Quintal_number) has been, predictably, debated. Linguist Susan McBurney argues that [American Sign Language](/American_Sign_Language) has a genuine [dual](/Dual_(grammatical_number)), but that the [trial](/Trial_number), [quadral](/Quadral_number), and [quintal](/Quintal_number) should instead be classified as numeral incorporation, rather than distinct [grammatical numbers](/Grammatical_category). Her reasoning is quite logical: the handshape for the [dual](/Dual_(grammatical_number)) marker is distinct from the numeral 'two,' unlike the higher number markers; these numerals can also be incorporated into other words (such as those for times or amounts); and the use of markers beyond the [dual](/Dual_(grammatical_number)) is not obligatory, with the [plural](/Plural) being an acceptable substitute. [168] Unfortunately, she lacked sufficient data to determine if these arguments applied equally to other [sign languages](/Sign_language). Linguist Raquel Veiga Busto, however, contends that they do *not* apply equally to [Catalan Sign Language](/Catalan_Language), and, for convenience, uses the terms [quadral](/Quadral_number) and [quintal](/Quintal_number) for the language's [pronouns](/Pronoun) without taking an official stance on whether they constitute true grammatical number or mere numeral incorporation [169]. A third model proposes categorizing these apparent trial/quadral/quintal forms as "cardinal plurals"—essentially, forms of the [grammatical plural number](/Grammatical_category) where the precise number of people is specified [170]. Other authors, in a move that suggests a weary acceptance of complexity, treat these concepts as perfectly equivalent, referring to pronoun numeral incorporation while still applying the terms [quadral](/Quadral_number) and [quintal](/Quintal_number) [142] [137].

Beyond five, some [sign language pronouns](/Pronoun) can even indicate higher specific numbers of referents. [Ugandan Sign Language](/Ugandan_Sign_Language) possesses a rare pronoun form for exactly six people [142]. Some [American Sign Language](/American_Sign_Language) speakers, when prompted, have incorporated numerals up to nine into inclusive [pronouns](/Pronoun) [171]. [Israeli Sign Language](/Israeli_Sign_Language) theoretically has the grammatical capacity to incorporate numerals up to ten into [pronouns](/Pronoun) [172]. The human desire for specificity, it seems, knows few bounds.

#### Greater plural

The [greater plural](/Plural) is a number category that exists beyond the standard [plural](/Plural), for when 'many' simply isn't enough. It has been variously, and rather poetically, termed the global plural, the remote plural, the plural of abundance [173], the unlimited plural [174], and the superplural [175]. In [Tswana language](/Tswana_language), for example, this looks like: [176]

*   *ntša* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"dog" (singular)
*   *di ntša* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"dogs" (plural)
*   *ma ntša* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"a very large number of dogs" (greater plural)

The [greater plural](/Plural) can also form a component of even larger, more complex number systems. Nouns in [Barngarla language](/Barngarla_language) boast a four-way distinction: singular, dual, plural, and greater plural [175]. The same four-way distinction is found in [Mokilese language](/Mokilese_language) [pronouns](/Pronoun), where a former [trial](/Trial_number) has evolved into a [plural](/Plural), leaving the original [plural](/Plural) to take on a [greater plural](/Plural) meaning [177]. A different four-way split—singular, paucal, plural, and greater plural—can be observed in some verbs of [Hualapai language](/Havasupai%E2%80%93Hualapai_language) [178]. A truly intricate system exists in [Mele-Fila language](/Mele-Fila_language): [pronouns](/Pronoun) distinguish singular, dual, plural, and greater plural, but [articles](/Article_(grammar)) attached to nouns differentiate singular, paucal, and plural. The result is a combined five-way distinction across full sentences: singular, dual, paucal, plural, and greater plural. Singular and plural maintain straightforward number agreements, but the dual uses dual pronouns with paucal articles; the paucal uses plural pronouns with paucal articles; and the greater plural uses greater plural pronouns with plural articles [179]. One can only assume this keeps speakers on their toes.

The [Mokilese pronouns](/Mokilese_language) system is another example of this layered approach:

| | Singular | Dual | Plural | Greater Plural |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| First (exc.) | ngoah/ngoahi | kama | kamai | kimi |
| First (inc.) | —N/a | kisa | kisai | kihs |
| Second | koah/koawoa | kamwa | kamwai | kimwi |
| Third | ih | ara/ira | arai/irai | ihr |

The precise meaning and terminology for the [greater plural](/Plural) diverge between languages. In some, like [Miya language](/Miya_language), it simply represents a large, unspecified quantity of something, earning it the moniker "plural of abundance." In others, such as [Kaytetye language](/Kaytetye_language), it can refer to *all* of something in existence, hence its designation as the "global plural" [180].

And, as with other grammatical numbers, languages vary in which [cases](/Grammatical_case) the [greater plural](/Plural) may be employed. It is more commonly found in nouns than in pronouns [179]. Accordingly, in [Kaytetye](/Kaytetye_language), the [greater plural](/Plural) is exclusive to nouns [181], while in [Mokilese](/Mokilese_language), it appears only in [pronouns](/Pronoun) [177] [182]. [Chamacoco language](/Chamacoco_language) restricts the [greater plural](/Plural) to first person inclusive [pronouns](/Pronoun), second person [pronouns](/Pronoun), and first person inclusive verb [inflections](/Inflection) [183]. [Tigre language](/Tigre_language) takes specificity to an extreme, using the [greater plural](/Plural) for only a single word: *nälät*, meaning "a large number of deer" [179].

#### Greatest plural

The [greatest plural](/Plural) is a number category that exists even *beyond* the [greater plural](/Plural). It has, rather unimaginatively, also been dubbed the "even greater plural." In [Warekena language](/Warekena_language), this extreme level of quantification is expressed as: [184] [185] [186]

*   *ʧinu* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"dog" (singular)
*   *ʧinu ne* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"dogs" (plural)
*   *ʧinu nawi* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"very many dogs" (greater plural)
*   *ʧinu nenawi* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"very many dogs indeed, so many one cannot count them" (greatest plural)

A similar system exists in [Banyun language](/Banyun_language), where the [greater plural](/Plural) signifies unlimitedness, and the [greatest plural](/Plural) represents "a higher degree of unlimitedness" [185]. Because, naturally, unlimitedness itself needs to be quantified.

Linguist Daniel Harbour, in an attempt to bring some order to this numerical chaos, has conceptualized the paucal, greater paucal, plural, greater plural, and greatest plural as being collectively definable by "cuts" that divide the spectrum of possible numbers into distinct sections. One low cut delineates [paucal](/Paucal_number) and [plural](/Plural), and one high cut separates [plural](/Plural) and [greater plural](/Plural). Two low cuts define [paucal](/Paucal_number), [greater paucal](/Paucal_number), and [plural](/Plural); one low cut and one high cut define [paucal](/Paucal_number), [plural](/Plural), and [greater plural](/Plural); and two high cuts define [plural](/Plural), [greater plural](/Plural), and [greatest plural](/Plural) [187]. Mercifully, there appears to be no language that employs three such cuts, and thus, no language with three [paucal categories](/Paucal_number) and an "even greater paucal" [188] [189].

Due to their inherently inexact definitions, the existence of multiple [plural categories](/Plural) can, rather predictably, blur the line between [paucal](/Paucal_number) and [plural](/Plural) [190] [191]. For example, [Mele-Fila language](/Mele-Fila_language) is said to have a [paucal](/Paucal_number), [plural](/Plural), and [greater plural](/Plural). However, the transition from [plural](/Plural) to [greater plural](/Plural) occurs around 15 to 20. This places the [Mele-Fila](/Mele-Fila_language) "plural" within the range of some larger "paucals" described in other languages. Thus, the distinction between a system of paucal, plural, greater plural, and a system of paucal, greater paucal, plural becomes somewhat muddied [191]. Further examples can be found in the related languages of [Northern Gumuz](/Gumuz_language) and [Daatsʼiin language](/Daats%CA%BCiin_language). [Northern Gumuz](/Gumuz_language) reportedly marks the [plural](/Plural) and [greater plural](/Plural) on verbs [192], while [Daatsʼiin](/Daats%CA%BCiin_language) marks "three degrees of plurality" (plural, greater plural, and greatest plural) on verbs [193]. In both languages, however, the "plural" often functions as a [paucal](/Paucal_number), understood to mean approximately two to four. Yet, this is not always the case, as the [Northern Gumuz paucal/plural](/Gumuz_language) can sometimes refer to "much greater than four" [194]. Consistency, it seems, is a luxury.

#### General, singulative, and plurative

(Main article: [Singulative number](/Singulative_number))

In some languages, the default form of a noun isn't singular, but rather *general*, a conveniently ambiguous category that doesn't specify number and could mean one or more than one. [citation needed] The singular and plural forms are then explicitly marked as derived from this general form. The general is employed when the specific number is deemed irrelevant or, more likely, too much effort to specify. In this system, the singular is often termed the *singulative*, to highlight its derivation from a different base. Similarly, the plural derived from the general is called the *plurative* [195]. The [Pular language](/Pular_language) illustrates this: [196]

*   *bare* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"dog(s)" (general, any number, a charming indifference to specificity)
*   *bare eru* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"dog" (singulative, finally, a single dog)
*   *bare eji* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"dogs" (plurative, a group explicitly marked as such)

However, some languages simplify further, maintaining only a two-way distinction between general and plurative, as seen in [Japanese language](/Japanese_language): [197]

*   *inu* (犬)&#160;&#8211;&#32;"dog(s)" (general, could be one, could be many, who cares?)
*   *inu tachi* (犬たち)&#160;&#8211;&#32;"dogs" (plurative, a clear, if belated, acknowledgment of multiplicity)

Less common, and perhaps more peculiar, is a two-way distinction solely between general and singulative. No language adopts this as its primary number contrast, though some languages feature specific nouns that exhibit this precise distinction [198]. For instance, in [Sidama language](/Sidama_language): [199]

*   *goto* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"hyena(s)" (general, a group of indeterminate size)
*   *got iiččo* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"hyena" (singulative, a single hyena, finally isolated)

In certain languages, like [Afar language](/Afar_language), a handful of nouns maintain a three-way contrast of general/singulative/plurative, while two-way contrasts of general/singulative and general/plurative are both quite common [200].

And, as if to prove that linguistic systems are rarely simple, there are languages that regularly combine these 'general' systems with dual, trial, paucal, or greater plural categories:

*   [Hamer language](/Hamer_language)&#160;&#8211;&#32;general, singulative, and paucal: [201]
    *   *qáski* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"dog(s)" (general, number unspecified)
    *   *qáski no* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"dog" (singulative, one specific dog)
    *   *qáski na* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"a few dogs" (paucal, a small, indeterminate group)

*   [Warlpiri language](/Warlpiri_language)&#160;&#8211;&#32;general, dual, and paucal: [202] [203]
    *   *maliki* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"dog(s)" (general)
    *   *maliki jarra* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"two dogs" (dual)
    *   *maliki patu* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"a few dogs" (paucal)

*   [Bambassi language](/Bambassi_language)&#160;&#8211;&#32;general, dual, and plurative: [204]
    *   *kané* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"dog(s)" (general)
    *   *kan kuw e* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"two dogs" (dual)
    *   *kan ol e* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"dogs" (plurative)

*   [Baiso language](/Baiso_language)&#160;&#8211;&#32;general, singulative, paucal, and plurative: [205] [206] [207]
    *   *ker* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"dog(s)" (general)
    *   *ker titi* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"dog" (singulative)
    *   *ker dʒedʒa* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"a few dogs" (paucal)
    *   *ker oor* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"dogs" (plurative)

*   [Arabana language](/Arabana_language)&#160;&#8211;&#32;general, dual, trial, and plurative: [208]
    *   *madla* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"dog(s)" (general)
    *   *madla pula* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"two dogs" (dual)
    *   *madla karikari* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"three dogs" (trial)
    *   *madla kari* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"dogs" (plurative)

*   [Kaytetye language](/Kaytetye_language)&#160;&#8211;&#32;general, dual, plurative, and greater plural: [209] [210] [211]
    *   *aleke* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"dog(s)" (general)
    *   *aleke therre* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"two dogs" (dual)
    *   *alek amerne* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"dogs" (plurative)
    *   *alek eynenge* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"all dogs" (greater plural)

Additional systems, even more specific, can be found for only certain nouns:

*   In [Burushaski](/Burushaski), for nouns that stubbornly maintain the same form in both singular and plural, the plural marker takes on the meaning of a [greater plural](/Plural): [212]
    *   *čhúmo* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"fish" (general, could be one, could be many, but not *too* many)
    *   *čhúmo muc* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"a quite large number of fish" (greater plural, now we're talking serious quantities)
*   Beyond general, singulative, and paucal, some nouns in [Hamer](/Hamer_language) feature an additional distinction, variously analyzed as a [greater plural](/Plural) [213] or a [collective plural](/Collective_noun) [214]. It appears to unambiguously denote a [greater plural](/Plural) in specific contexts, such as: [215]
    *   *hámar* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"Hamer person/people" (general)
    *   *hamar tâ* (m) / *hamar tóno* (f)&#160;&#8211;&#32;"Hamer person" (singulative)
    *   *hámar ra* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"a few Hamer people" (paucal)
    *   *hámar ro* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"all Hamer people" (greater plural, a rather definitive statement)
*   Some Arabic dialects even feature a few nouns that exhibit a five-way distinction: general, singulative, dual, plurative, and greater plural. In [Damascus Arabic](/Damascus_Arabic), for instance: [190]
    *   *dəbbān* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"fly/flies" (general)
    *   *dəbbān e* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"fly" (singulative)
    *   *dəbbān tēn* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"two flies" (dual)
    *   *dəbbān āt* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"flies" (plurative)
    *   *d a ba bī n* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"many flies" (greater plural, an overwhelming swarm)

#### Minimal, unit augmented, and augmented

These number categories, minimal, unit augmented, and augmented, constitute a distinct paradigm, typically applied to [pronouns](/Pronoun) in languages where a first person dual inclusive pronoun is grammatically treated identically to singular pronouns, and a first person trial inclusive pronoun behaves like dual pronouns. It's a relative system, designed to replace the absolute paradigm of singular, dual, trial, and plural when that framework simply doesn't fit the language's internal logic.

For example, under a traditional singular/dual/trial/plural analysis, the [pronouns](/Pronoun) in [Ilocano language](/Ilocano_language) [216] [217] and [Bininj Kunwok](/Bininj_Kunwok) [218] appear somewhat "inelegant," as the linguists so delicately put it:

| Ilocano pronouns | Singular | Dual | Plural |
|---|---|---|---|
| First (exc.) | co | —N/a | mi |
| First (inc.) | —N/a | ta | tayo |
| Second | mo | —N/a | yo |
| Third | na | —N/a | da |

| Bininj Kunwok pronouns | Singular | Dual | Trial | Plural |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| First (exc.) | ngarduk | ngarrewoneng | —N/a | ngadberre |
| First (inc.) | —N/a | ngarrgu | garriwoneng | gadberre |
| Second | nguddanggi | ngurriwoneng | —N/a | ngudberre |
| Third | nuye/ngarre | berrewoneng | —N/a | bedberre |

The category of "singular" simply doesn't exist for the first person inclusive, which, by its very definition, must involve at least two people. In [Ilocano](/Ilocano_language), the "dual" is exclusively for first person inclusive, and similarly for the "trial" in [Bininj Kunwok](/Bininj_Kunwok). Such categorizations, as noted, have been described as "inelegant." [218] More critically, this absolute framework can poorly reflect the underlying grammatical structure: for instance, [Bininj Kunwok](/Bininj_Kunwok) treats the first person inclusive "trial" (referring to three people) identically to the "duals" in other persons, using the same suffix *-woneng*.

The more accurate, alternate analysis, therefore, reorganizes these into a relative paradigm:

| Ilocano pronouns | Minimal | Augmented |
|---|---|---|
| First (exc.) | co | mi |
| First (inc.) | ta | tayo |
| Second | mo | yo |
| Third | na | da |

| Bininj Kunwok pronouns | Minimal | Unit augmented | Augmented |
|---|---|---|---|
| First (exc.) | ngarduk | ngarrewoneng | ngadberre |
| First (inc.) | ngarrgu | garriwoneng | gadberre |
| Second | nguddanggi | ngurriwoneng | ngudberre |
| Third | nuye/ngarre | berrewoneng | bedberre |

The 'minimal' number represents the smallest possible group for each respective category. For first exclusive, second, and third persons, this is, logically, one. For first inclusive, it is two. 'Unit augmented' then signifies one more than the minimal. Thus, for first exclusive, second, and third persons, this means two, and for first inclusive, it means three. 'Augmented' functions as the equivalent of a general plural. In a minimal/augmented system, 'augmented' means more than one for first exclusive, second, and third persons, and more than two for first inclusive. In a minimal/unit augmented/augmented system, 'augmented' means more than two for first exclusive, second, and third persons, and more than three for first inclusive. It's a system that requires a certain amount of mental gymnastics, but it works.

Besides [Ilocano](/Ilocano_language), other languages considered to employ a minimal/augmented pronoun system include [Tagalog language](/Tagalog_language) [219] [220], [Maranao language](/Maranao_language) [221], [Maskelynes language](/Maskelynes_language) [222], and [Ho-Chunk language](/Ho-Chunk_language) [223]. The more elaborate three-way distinction, incorporating 'unit augmented,' is predominantly found in [Australian Aboriginal languages](/Australian_Aboriginal_languages), particularly non-Pama-Nyungan languages [224] [j]. Among the very few languages outside Australia to feature this system are the Austronesian language [Äiwoo](/%C3%84iwoo_language) [224] [237] and the [Trans–New Guinea language](/Trans%E2%80%93New_Guinea_languages) of [Kunimaipa language](/Kunimaipa_language) [224] [238].

The minimal and augmented categories can also combine with [paucal](/Paucal_number) to form a three-way pronoun system of minimal, paucal, and augmented/plural. This is reportedly the case with [Kayapo language](/Kayapo_language) [239] [240]. A four-way system of minimal, unit augmented, paucal, and plural is theoretically possible, but, thankfully, has never actually been observed in any natural language [240].

#### Composed numbers

Composed numbers are precisely what they sound like: number categories meticulously constructed from the combination of multiple existing number markers. They are, as one might expect, "a rare phenomenon." [241] Because why be simple when you can be complex?

##### Dual and plural

In [Breton language](/Breton_language): [241]

*   *lagad* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"eye" (singular)
*   *daou lagad* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"two eyes" (dual)
*   *lagad où* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"eyes" (plural)
*   *daou lagad où* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"pairs of eyes" (composed, dual + plural)

[Breton](/Breton_language) restricts its [dual](/Dual_(grammatical_number)) to nouns that naturally occur in pairs, primarily body parts and items of clothing. The composed dual and plural, *daou lagad où*, signifies multiple *sets* of two each, whereas the regular plural, *lagad où*, simply refers to multiple items without implying they come in pairs [242]. There is at least one documented instance in [Ancient Egyptian](/Egyptian_language), from an inscription dating to the reign of [Merneptah](/Merneptah), of this exact grammatical construction applied to the word "hand" (to mean multiple pairs of hands) [243]. It seems the ancients also appreciated a good linguistic flourish.

A similar, though semantically inverted, category exists in some nouns of [Classical Arabic](/Classical_Arabic), where it is termed the "dual of the plural." Instead of multiple sets of two, it indicates two sets of multiple items each. Thus, one finds: *rumḥun*, spear (singular); *rumḥani*, two spears (dual); *rimāḥun*, spears (plural); and *rimāḥāni*, two groups of spears (dual of the plural) [244] [245]. The Arabic dual of the plural specifically implies a minimum of six items, or two groups of three each [244]. Because, naturally, counting in groups of three is far more interesting than simple pairs.

##### Plural and plural

In [Breton](/Breton_language) [241] and [Classical Arabic](/Classical_Arabic) [246] [247], as well as in [Somali language](/Somali_language) [248] and [Maasai language](/Maasai_language) [249], some nouns are permitted to compound the plural with itself, signifying multiple *different* groups. This has been called the "plural of the plural," the plural plural, or, with a certain dramatic flair, the double plural [246] [247]. An Arabic example clarifies this: *kalb*, dog (singular); *aklub*, dogs (plural); and *akālib*, groups of dogs (double plural) [250]. The Arabic double plural implies a minimum of nine items, or three groups of three each. Some [Classical Arabic](/Classical_Arabic) nouns can even take this to an extreme, pluralizing the plural *again*, creating the "plural plural plural," or triple plural. For instance: *firqat*, sect (singular); *firaq*, sects (plural); *ʔafrāq*, groups of sects (double plural); and *ʔafārīq*, groups of groups of sects (triple plural). The triple plural, naturally, implies a minimum of 27 items [251]. According to the 15th-century linguist and polymath [Jalal al-Din al-Suyuti](/Al-Suyuti), the Arabic word for male camel, *jamalun*, could be cumulatively pluralized up to *six* times: *ʔajmulun* (plural), *ʔajmālun* (double plural), *jāmilun* (triple plural), *jimālun* (quadruple plural), *jimālatun* (quintuple plural), and *jimālātun* (sextuple plural) [252] [k]. One can only assume such precision was essential for camel traders.

#### Conflated numbers

Conflated numbers are categories formed by the rather messy combination of other existing categories. They have only ever been attested as secondary phenomena, appearing alongside other established grammatical number systems within a language. They've been rather aptly named "conflated numbers" [257].

##### Singular-dual

A few languages possess specific parts of speech that distinguish between two number categories: 'one or two,' and 'more than two.' The former category can be conceptualized as a single, conflated singular-dual number [257]. In the nouns of [Kalaw Lagaw Ya](/Kalaw_Lagaw_Ya), for instance: [258] [259]

*   *ùmay* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"dog(s)" (one or two, a convenient ambiguity)
*   *ùmay l* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"dogs" (plural, three or more, finally committing to multiplicity)

The [pronouns](/Pronoun) and [verbs](/Verb) of [Kalaw Lagaw Ya](/Kalaw_Lagaw_Ya), however, maintain a distinction between singular, dual, and plural, thus leaving no ambiguity between one and two in full sentences [258]. It seems the language merely shifts the burden of specificity.

While [Kalaw Lagaw Ya](/Kalaw_Lagaw_Ya) applies the singular-dual to all its nouns, [Central Pame](/Pame_languages) restricts it specifically to inanimate nouns. Consider *č ihàgŋ*, spoon(s) (one or two), versus *š ihàgŋ*, spoons (plural, three or more). Pame animate nouns, in contrast, largely maintain a full three-way distinction: *n adò*, dog (singular); *n adò i*, two dogs (dual); and *l adò t*, dogs (plural) [260].

The singular-dual can also manifest in verbs. [Hopi language](/Hopi_language) verbs distinguish between singular-dual and plural (3+), while [Hopi](/Hopi_language) [pronouns](/Pronoun) differentiate singular and plural (2+). The [dual](/Dual_(grammatical_number)) can then be represented by combining a [plural pronoun](/Pronoun) with a singular-dual verb. This curious phenomenon has been termed a "constructed number" [261] or, more colorfully, a "Frankendual" [262]. However, [Hopi nouns](/Hopi_language) still overtly distinguish singular, dual, and plural. [Idi language](/Idi_language) takes this a step further, possessing no specific [dual markers](/Dual_(grammatical_number)) whatsoever for any part of speech; the only way to express the [dual](/Dual_(grammatical_number)) is by combining a singular-dual verb with a plural noun [263]. A more complex example comes from [Koasati language](/Koasati_language), where, alongside a general plural, some verbs have singular and dual forms, others only singular, and some only singular-dual: [264]

| Some Koasati verbs | | | |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Verb** | **Singular** | **Dual** | **Plural** |
| "to sit" | cokkó:lin | cikkí:kan | í:san |
| "to run" | walí:kan | | tóɬkan |
| "to die" | íllin | | hápkan |
| "to go" | mi’a | mimi’a | mi’a |

##### Singular-dual-trial

In the [Tucanoan language](/Tucanoan_languages) of [Tuyuca language](/Tuyuca_language), inanimate classifiers (which, rather conveniently, attach to nouns) distinguish between one to three items versus more than three: [265] [266]

*   *hoópór o* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"banana(s)" (one to three, a charmingly broad category)
*   *hoópór i* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"bananas" (plural, four or more, finally a proper group)

The related [Tucanoan language](/Tucanoan_languages) of [Wanano language](/Wanano_language) also features some nouns that operate in this manner [267] [268].

This same numerical distinction is also observed in the verb for "climb" in [Miriwoong language](/Miriwoong_language), an [Australian language](/Australian_languages) [68].

##### Singular-dual-trial-quadral

In [Piratapuyo language](/Wanano_language), a language closely related to [Wanano](/Wanano_language), some nouns with inanimate classifiers distinguish between one to four items versus more than four: [267] [269] [270]

*   *pika* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"finger(s)" (one to four, a surprisingly inclusive count)
*   *pika ri* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"fingers" (plural, five or more, for when you need to be *really* specific)

##### Singular-paucal

[Zuni language](/Zuni_language), much like [Hopi](/Hopi_language), exhibits a singular-dual versus plural distinction in its verbs. A plural noun combined with a nonplural verb indicates a [dual](/Dual_(grammatical_number)). However, the inverse combination—a nonplural noun with a plural verb—is also possible, and can be interpreted with frustrating variability as one, two, or a few. Thus, [Zuni nouns](/Zuni_language) have been described as possessing a "singular-paucal" versus plural distinction [271] [272].

Some nouns in [Navajo language](/Navajo_language) have also been described as functioning in this manner, such as: [273]

*   *kǫ* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"fire(s)" (one or several, maintaining a convenient vagueness)
*   *daa kǫ* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"fires" (many, finally committing to a large quantity)

Similarly, although [Larike pronouns](/Wakasihu_language) display singular, dual, trial, and plural forms, they are restricted to human referents. For nonhuman referents, only two possible numbers exist, marked on the verb: a plural, and a "singular" that can encompass anywhere from one to a few [265]. It seems that nonhumans are simply less deserving of numerical precision.

##### Nondual

The [nondual](/Nondual_number) [l] number means any number *except* two. Because sometimes, the most important thing to state is what something *isn't*. In [Wangkumara language](/Wilson_River_language), for example: [276]

*   *d̯it̯i*&#160;&#8211;&#32;"dog(s)" (nondual, one or three or more than three, just not two)
*   *d̯it̯i bula* &#160;&#8211;&#32;"two dogs" (dual, specifically two)

[Wangkumara](/Wilson_River_language) does not typically mark number directly on nouns. Instead, it distinguishes singular, dual, and plural through [adnominal pronouns](/Pronoun), plural-indicating adjectives like 'many,' or marking on other adjectives. The notable exception is that nouns take the [dual enclitic](/Dual_(grammatical_number)) when referring to two. Thus, for nouns alone, the only effective distinction is dual and nondual [276].

A more complex system is found in the [Tanoan languages](/Tanoan_languages) of [Kiowa language](/Kiowa_language) and [Jemez language](/Jemez_language). These languages employ what is termed an inverse number system. While they distinguish between singular, dual, and plural, any given noun is only assigned a single possible number marker. The specific number implicit in an unmarked noun then depends entirely on its class. In [Kiowa](/Kiowa_language), by default, Class I nouns are singular-dual, Class II nouns are plural (two or more), Class III nouns are dual, and Class IV nouns are [mass nouns](/Mass_noun) with no number. The inverse number marker then shifts the noun to whatever number(s) the unmarked noun *isn't*, such as transforming Class III nouns from dual to nondual [277]. In [Jemez](/Jemez_language), Class III nouns operate in reverse: they are inherently nondual and are specifically marked for dual [278]. It's a system designed to keep linguists employed.

| Example Kiowa nouns [279] | | | |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Class** | **Noun** | **Singular** | **Dual** | **Plural** |
| I | bug | pól | | pól dau |
| II | stick | | áa dau | áa |
| III | tomato | | k’âun dau | k’âun |
| IV | rock | ts’ów | | |

| Some Jemez nouns [280] | | | |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Class** | **Noun** | **Singular** | **Dual** | **Plural** |
| I | crow | kyáá | kyáá sh | |
| II | bridge | wáákwe sh | | wáákwe |
| III | flower | pá | pá sh | pá |
| IV | snow | zú | | |

The nondual versus dual distinction can also be found in verbs. [Timbisha language](/Timbisha_language) features verbs with several different possible number distinctions, including nondual ones [281]. A more minor example is [Forest Enets](/Enets_language), which restricts the nondual to its intransitive third person imperative verbs [282].

| Example Timbisha verbs | | | |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Verb** | **Singular** | **Dual** | **Plural** |
| "to emerge" | to’e | toto’e | kɨa |
| "to fall" | pahe | | pokoa |
| "to kill" | pakka | | wasɨ |
| "to go" | mi’a | mimi’a | mi’a |

The nondual, rather inconveniently, violates a proposed universal of conflated systems, which posits that they will always encompass every value *except* plural [283]. Regardless, the nondual has still been referred to as a conflation of number values [284]. Because, in linguistics, even violations get a name.

#### Numberless languages

A small, and arguably more sensible, number of languages completely eschew [grammatical number](/Grammatical_category), even in [pronouns](/Pronoun). A well-known example of this refreshing minimalism is [Pirahã language](/Pirah%C3%A3_language). [Acehnese language](/Acehnese_language) comes close, but, in a minor concession to specificity, appears to maintain a singular/plural distinction only in its first person [pronouns](/Pronoun) [285].

The [Pirahã pronouns](/Pirah%C3%A3_language) offer a stark example of this simplicity:

| | |
|---|---|
| First | ti |
| Second | gíxai |
| Third | hiapióxio |

It’s almost as if they decided that life was complicated enough without adding unnecessary numerical distinctions.

